---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import portrait from "@/assets/portrait.png";
---

<section class="section" id="about">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="section-head">
      <div>
        <div class="section-num">
          <span class="folio">i.</span>
          <span class="rule"></span>§ 01 — About
        </div>
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-title">A practitioner <em>first.</em> Architect when the system demands it.</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="about-grid">
      <figure class="portrait">
        <Image
          src={portrait}
          alt="Frankie Ramirez"
          widths={[300, 480, 640]}
          sizes="(max-width: 820px) 100vw, 240px"
          loading="lazy"
        />
        <figcaption class="portrait-label">// frankie, 2026</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <div class="about-body">
        <p>I've spent the last fourteen years writing frontend code in the kind of places where an interface is a liability as much as an asset — CRM platforms, proptech dashboards, SaaS consoles. The kind of products where a thousand users notice when a button moves.</p>
        <p>What I've found is that <b>the interesting problems live one layer down</b> from the visual surface. How components compose. How state flows. How a design system stays legible when forty engineers are contributing to it simultaneously. How you onboard the forty-first.</p>
        <p>I'm most useful on teams that care about <b>craft and velocity</b> — where the refactor is a valid deliverable, where design and engineering argue well, and where "how does this feel in the hand" is a sentence people say out loud in code review.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Pull quote -->
<section class="pullquote">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="pullquote-inner">
      <div class="pullquote-mark">“</div>
      <div>
        <blockquote>
          The interesting problems live <em>one layer down</em> from the visual surface — in how components compose, how state flows, how a system stays legible when forty engineers are contributing to it.
        </blockquote>
        <cite>— Frankie, on the job</cite>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
